{
  "answer": "**The closest match in Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib* appears in ghazal 145 (\"Na hoga yak-biyabaan maandagi se zauq kam mera\").**\n\nThis couplet evokes life's transience and aimlessness, likening the speaker to \"road-dust\" while cautioning against seeking lasting lessons in illusions (a mirage, symbolizing fleeting worldly experiences):\n\n> Seek not a lesson in a mirage you can't retrace,  \n> I am but road-dust, aimless is my winding pace, my.[^1]\n\nNo exact phrasing like \"life's lesson\" paired directly with \"dust of the road\" appears in the English translations of the *Diwan*. Searches for variations (\"dust road,\" \"road dust,\" \"life's lesson,\" etc.) yielded no closer results in Ghalib's 239 ghazals. This may be a loose recollection or paraphrase of the above, common in discussions of Ghalib's themes of existential wandering.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/145-na-hoga-yak-biyabaan-maandagi-se-zauq-kam-mera/translation/#p-26d938).\n\n[^2]: The corpus includes full translations of all ghazals; broader searches across Ghalib confirmed no other relevant couplets.",
